        <font size='4'><b>PRACTICE YOUR SHOPPING-CART DANCE</b></font><br>
                                <img src='http://graphics.millsberry.com/site_gfx/interiors/gazette/gazette_20090416.jpg' border='1' width='280' height='200'>
                        </div>
        <div id='gazette_byline'><em>By Audrey Smythe-Wei<br>Editor-in-Chief</em></div>
        <b>Thursday, April 16, 2009</b> &mdash;
    Grocery shopping can be refreshing! You can plan out your week item by item, try new foods, and plot your mission to eat healthier. <br><br>Soon it will be even easier to do your food shopping in town. Renovations are underway at the <a href="http://www.millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=4">Millsberry Grocery Store</a>, and you can expect to see a fresh new look in just two weeks! Say goodbye to bumper-carts and say hello to breathing room, with roomier, well-organized aisles. You can also look forward to sampling a variety products not carried before.<br><br>And no worries about stocking up on your favorite food in the meantime&mdash;renovations are taking place after hours&mdash;though some (sleepy) citizens have expressed mixed feelings about the accommodation.<br><br>&quot;I hear them working on the store when I&#039;m trying to get some shut-eye,&quot; explained one neighborhood resident. &quot;But it&#039;ll be worth it. Last week I must have said &#039;<i>Excuse me</i>&#039; or &#039;<i>I&#039;m sorry</i>&#039; 20 times because of the overcrowding. Now I hear there&#039;ll be much more room. They say that instead of bumping into other shoppers, that we&#039;ll be able to boogie down the aisles, so I&#039;m looking forward to that.&quot;<br>
<br>
We found another local shopper peeking through the store windows after hours. &quot;I was told that the new products were top secret, but I heard something about a section devoted to space food! It&#039;s heightened my curiosity to try it&mdash;and I bet it&#039;s really handy for snacking on-the-go.&quot;<br><br><i>Space food</i>?! We&#039;re not so sure&mdash;but anything is possible, especially since <a href="http://www.millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=8">Hardware Store</a> owner Pete Peterson and <a href="http://www.millsberry.com/shop.phtml?shop_id=4">Grocery Store</a> owner Harold Ettin are collaborating on the plan. The <i><i>Gazette</i></i> caught up with them both in <a href="http://www.millsberry.com/peabody_park/">Peabody Park</a>, where they were looking over some blueprints, on a recent afternoon.<br><br>Ettin noted, &quot;This has always been a long-term dream of mine. I was thrilled when Mayor Wright wanted to invest in a redesign of the store. I think he&#039;s our most frequent shopper. He&#039;s obsessed with cereals&mdash;especially Count Chocula&reg;&mdash;so it&#039;ll come as no surprise that we&#039;re getting a bunch of new ones in!&quot;<br><br>Seconds later, Ettin fell asleep right on Peterson&#039;s shoulder. <br><br>Peterson explained, &quot;He&#039;s been working day and night on the store&mdash;so he&#039;s pretty exhausted.&quot; Then he asked if we&#039;d be willing to help carry him home.<br><br>We tried to get some more information out of the hardware handler, but mum was the word. &quot;I&#039;ll let Harold fill you in on all the juicy details another time&mdash;when he&#039;s more awake. However, I can tell you that the original plan was to make the store <i>the shape of a big bagel</i>! The Mayor didn&#039;t go for it though&mdash;he didn&#039;t like the idea of a big hole in the middle.&quot;<br><br>Well, that news nearly burst our bubble&mdash;or <i>bagel</i>, for that matter&mdash;but whatever its shape, the new store is bound to be a success. We hope to get more clues from Harold Ettin, but for now, we&#039;ll let him catch up on his ZZZs.
    </div>

